"I like going to the supermarkets to explore and try new food.

Today I decide to try again the expensive avocado since it is on promotion, buy 1 free 1 @ $8.95. Hopefully it is good experience this time.

Korean luncheon meat, i had a tiny bit the last time I bought, she ate most of it...the girl who loves pork.... It is nice, decided to buy another @anonymised_user on special.

Mala fried black bean fish, I bought to try but he finished and told me it is nice. Thus bought one to try. This one not on special but something new.

One nice thing about living in this cosmopolitan city is the ability to buy and try many types of food from many countries."

"Sunday 30.05.2021

1. Create the right environment and it will happen. Everyday my visitor comes and rest for a little while. 
2-3. Neighborhood's flowers.
4. My grocery shop's owner's pet trying to nap.
5. I wonder who is the planter? New tomato is growing....
6-10. My evening solo walk. 

My body was tensed today. Not sure if it was the jab or stress. The evening walk was very much needed.

In the morning I read this lady's instagram story sharing her son's long moment with the sinking Titanic....>45 mins.

And I thought...how often we adult stay with something that long? 

May be it was his way of coping, his safe space....May be we adult should try it.

Today I had the opportunity to try it. 
I spent 10 mins with today's sunset. 

My longest with sunset. 

In awe with nature. Magic.

Thank you universe and  @anonymised_user"

"Yesterday, not in the mood to even listen to him cause I was in my own discomfort.

This morning, we had bao for breakfast.

'please pack 8 for my golf kaki. ' he said.

Feeling so much better...in the mood for conversation.

This morning breakfast conversation went like this. 

' I have decided to give up struggle. ' I said.
' what are you struggling with? ' he asked.
' the business environment, cashflow, sales, salary, uncertainty.....' I answered.

'everybody struggles to a certain degree. ' he said.

' my mum will tell you she is struggling too because she needs to take care of the house without help from my dad. ' he continued.

'the house is too big for 2 of them. ' i said and thought to myself, lesson learnt here...not to have too big a house when I am older.

He is right. Everyone has struggle.....

Reading @anonymised_user sharing made me further realised that it is one's intention and one's capacity to love that decide if it is a struggle or not.
"

"I sometimes buy toto when the queue is not long.

'Quick Pick TOTO $1.00'

Of course I made several mistakes :
1. Bought system 7 without knowing it until I had to pay.
2. Checked the wrong draw date until a friend pointed out.
3. Found out need to say quick pick toto cause there is also quick pick 4D.

I always thought I have to have 4 numbers to win and he told me the same...'you need at least 3 + 1 additional number'

But I decided to google to check.
Trusting is good..checking is even better.

He was wrong. I had been wrong the whole time!

Only 3 numbers to win. Small prize $10.00 but still it is a WIN.

I won $10.00 and used the prize money to buy more quick pick.

And then I won another 3 numbers...another $10.00 the second time.

It reminded me of the sweep ticket story several years ago.

I used to buy one sweep ticket @anonymised_user of my way to connect to the memory of my childhood and my dad.(I dont now since they change the system. Too complicated...not as fun)

During one difficult business period....for the sweep ticket I bought, I won the last 4 numbers with a prize money of $6.00. I continued to buy with the prize number....I kept winning $6.00 for one year!

It was comforting cause it felt like a sign to ask me to hang in there...

Today it reminded me of that comfort with this 2nd winning ticket.

And this time, my heart is full and light and grateful.

Actually it is quite fun to join the queue and listen to the conversation between the  customers and the toto ticket seller. They know each other quite well. 

Wo Men Ge Zi Huo Zai Zi Ji De Xiao Shi Jie Nei ,Zai Mou Yi Ge Shi Guang Dian Yin Chu Zai Xiang Tong De Kong Jian Er Rang Ge Zi De Sheng Ming Peng Shang ,Ke Neng Jiu Shi Na Yao Ji Miao Zhong . 

I wonder if I had thrown any winning tickets of 3 numbers before this?"

"Let's talk about butter bread and avocado.

Being a homemaker since 20 years ago, buying grocery, cooking everyday, I see the change.

Bread
1.Used to be boring, not much choices. These days, a lot of choices and still new ones to come. 
2.Yesterday I bought this new bread and it is nice and cheap @ $1.50.
3. I saw chinese words. Quan Mai Mian Bao .Now they include chinese words. 
4. This is produced in Malaysia for Singapore supermarket, NTUC

Butter
1. Used to be boring, not much choices. 
I only bought SCS.
These days, a lot of choices and still new ones to come.
2. The price has increased from below $4 to $7 for a block of 250 butter.
3. Now we have weight of 250g, 220g and 200g.
4. Now we have butter from Australian, New Zealand, France...
5. I can now buy French butter for the same price or even cheaper than SCS. It has been a while since I ate SCS butter.

Avocado
1. Used to be boring, not much choices. Only Australian avocado @anonymised_user $2.50 each
These days we have avocado from Australia, New Zealand, mexico....and their quality has improved to be comparable to Australian Avocado.
2. Now I pay between $1 to $1.50 for an avocado.

And then, there are fresh milk, kiwi fruits, cheese, broccoli, orange, apple, strawberries..... All kinds of fruits and vegetables.

I guess... This is the benefit of capitalism, globalization.

But.... How can business survives long term if the competition is so fierce and price is one important factor for consumer to choose cause the difference between products have narrowed? 

And I heard my kids said to me the other day about sustainability.

 Sustainability."

"Once in a blue moon, I get to work some magic in the kitchen. Thankful that @anonymised_user mum let me use any ingredient I fancy in the kitchen. After a quick assessment, HZ and I decided to create a 3 dish meal - 

potato noodles with seaweed, dumplings, mushrooms and Mani Cai leaves; 

cucumber and four-angled beans with chilli, garlic and balsamic vinegar; and 

kimchi.

The Mani Cai leaves, cucumber, four-angled beans, chilli are harvests from gardens we care for.  

The noodles and balsamic vinegar were rescued items.

The kimchi was purchased but I am thankful to experience taking it out of the glass container and cutting a roll of kimchi as our third dish. It reminded me the value of preserving your fresh produce and the value of having such healthy options in the kitchen. 

It reminds me of having a minimal waste kitchen. It is not quite zero waste yet but at least the plastic is recycled (we hope), the used water is collected for watering the plants, and the food scraps are composted in soil. 

#kitchenadventures #thankful"

"Curating a virtual garden tour series. @anonymised_user whom I invited to organise a session with me, invited me to check out a garden she frequently told me about. As I walked in, I came to realise this was no ordinary garden. It is a garden with many stories and many things. I was most interested in the family story. 

This is a garden and learning space rented by a family business. A sibling does 3D sculptures. There are photos of his work and I easily recognised at least 2 of them. Another sibling pointed out her hand-drawn illustration of flowering plants. 

The ladies, whom I was introduced to today, were really friendly. They are happy to make friends, chat and exchange knowledge. I went home with two gifts - a potted plant and a plant bearing seeds. 

This garden is quite a distance from where I stay but I would love to come again and interact with the family and hear their stories.

#gardenobservations"

"Milestone moment for @anonymised_user , a community food scrap composting project by contributors of @anonymised_user 

Some of us in the Collective were making compost in our own homes and community gardens. Helping others outside our own 'hood to kick-start Compost Hubs seemed like a far-away dream. 

Today, I had the opportunity to be part of a 10-min FB live chat with Jeremy of Jurong Lake Gardens, LY (allotment gardener and compost maker), and host Kris @anonymised_user

The live chat comes after several months of journeying with a small group of Jurong Lake Gardens volunteers and allotment gardeners, and guiding them to become confident compost makers and foodscrappers. We started off as trainers. We experimented new ideas with them. Over time, we become friends who simply enjoy each other's presence. It is heartwarming to hear how some were inspired to kick-start similar community compost initiatives in their own residential estates.  

Groundwork discussions with Jurong Lake Gardens to encourage community-based composting at the national garden started back in 2019. This was before Project Black Gold became a project where we could collaborate and reach for our individual and shared goals. 

#community #compost #JurongLakeGardens #thankful #sgcompoststory"

"Second time at making rings that we would treasure. Thankful for the guidance of Lyn from @anonymised_user

This second making experience is less scary. I find myself at ease with using the vernier caliper (last used in school) and various tools. There are moments where @anonymised_user and I had to work together as a team  

Both ring making sessions are special. The first session was scary (deal with the dust, new machines, loud sound, fear of being cut by moving metal and all). It represented us taking a huge step forward as a couple and making a silent commitment to walk our life journey together. The second session represented us completing this step and ready to take the next step forward.

The choice of wood rings was intentional. We originally looked for options to make our own metal rings. It was difficult to know the source of metal which was a concern. Wood rings became our choice as wood at Studio MUYU are rescued from locally cut trees. It is as environmentally sustainable an option as you can get for rings. That wood may not last as long as metal is not of key concern as one can always make a new pair of rings. While we do intend to treasure the rings, it is the symbolism and the relationship that we treasure rather than the physical ring itself. 

The entire process supports us in working together as a couple and creating meaningful moments that we will remember. 

#couplerings #whatwevalue"
